        </div></div></gfg-carousel><h2 id=3D"types-of-logistic-regression" =
style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Types of Logistic Regression</span></h2><p =
dir=3D"ltr"><span>Logistic regression can be classified into three main typ=
es based on the nature of the dependent variable:</span></p><ol><li value=
=3D"1"><b><strong>Binomial Logistic Regression</strong></b><span>: This typ=
e is used when the dependent variable has only two possible categories. Exa=
mples include Yes/No, Pass/Fail or 0/1. It is the most common form of logis=
tic regression and is used for binary classification problems.</span></li><=
li value=3D"2"><b><strong>Multinomial Logistic Regression</strong></b><span=
>: This is used when the dependent variable has three or more possible cate=
gories that are not ordered. For example, classifying animals into categori=
es like "cat," "dog" or "sheep." It extends the binary logistic regression =
to handle multiple classes.</span></li><li value=3D"3"><b><strong>Ordinal L=
ogistic Regression</strong></b><span>: This type applies when the dependent=
 variable has three or more categories with a natural order or ranking. Exa=
mples include ratings like "low," "medium" and "high." It takes the order o=
f the categories into account when modeling.</span></li></ol><h2 id=3D"assu=
mptions-of-logistic-regression" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Assumptions=
 of Logistic Regression </span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Understanding the =
assumptions behind logistic regression is important to ensure the model is =
applied correctly, main assumptions are:</span></p><ol><li value=3D"1"><b><=
strong>Independent observations</strong></b><span>: Each data point is assu=
med to be independent of the others means there should be no correlation or=
 dependence between the input samples.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><b><stron=
g>Binary dependent variables</strong></b><span>: It takes the assumption th=
at the dependent variable must be binary, means it can take only two values=
. For more than two categories </span><a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.=
org/deep-learning/what-is-softmax-classifier/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener"><span>SoftMax </span></a><span>functions are used.</span></li><li va=
lue=3D"3"><b><strong>Linearity relationship between independent variables a=
nd log odds</strong></b><span>: The model assumes a linear relationship bet=
ween the independent variables and the log odds of the dependent variable w=
hich means the predictors affect the log odds in a linear way.</span></li><=
li value=3D"4"><b><strong>No outliers</strong></b><span>: The dataset shoul=
d not contain extreme outliers as they can distort the estimation of the lo=
gistic regression coefficients.</span></li><li value=3D"5"><b><strong>Large=
 sample size</strong></b><span>: It requires a sufficiently large sample si=
ze to produce reliable and stable results.</span></li></ol><h2 id=3D"unders=
tanding-sigmoid-function" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Understandin=
g Sigmoid Function</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>1. The sigmoid fun=
ction is a important part of logistic regression which is used to convert t=
he raw output of the model into a probability value between 0 and 1. </span=
></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>2. This function takes any real number and maps i=
t into the range 0 to 1 forming an "S" shaped curve called the sigmoid curv=
e or logistic curve. Because probabilities must lie between 0 and 1, the si=
gmoid function is perfect for this purpose.</span></p><div id=3D"GFG_AD_Des=
ktop_InContent_ATF_728x280" style=3D"text-align: center; margin: 10px 0px;"=
></div><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>3. In logistic regression, we use a threshold v=
alue usually 0.5 to decide the class label.</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><=
span>If the sigmoid output is same or above the threshold, the input is cla=
ssified as Class 1.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>If it is below the thr=
eshold, the input is classified as Class 0.</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr">=
<span>This approach helps to transform continuous input values into meaning=
ful class predictions.</span></p><h2 id=3D"how-does-logistic-regression-wor=
k" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>How does Logistic Regression work?</span=
></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Logistic regression model transforms the </span>=
<a href=3D"https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/ml-linear-regress=
ion/" rel=3D"noopener"><span>linear regression</span></a><span> function co=
ntinuous value output into categorical value output using a sigmoid functio=
n which maps any real-valued set of independent variables input into a valu=
e between 0 and 1. This function is known as the logistic function.</span><=
/p><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Suppose we have input features represented as a mat=
rix:</span></p><p style=3D"text-align: center; overflow: auto hidden; paddi=
